Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>Do you look beyond the brand when you buy a new dress or shirt? It is difficult to think about, but important to understand that when it comes to what you are wearing - it&rsquo;s not just about your clothes, but the&nbsp;materials and chemicals used to make them.&nbsp;</p>
<p>One of the most used raw materials of the fashion industry &ndash; Cotton, is also the one of the most pesticide-intensive crops. It requires massive quantities of pesticides and water when compared with other crops. 85 % of the daily needs in water of the entire population of India would be covered by the water used to grow cotton in the country.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The fashion industry is cited as the second-most polluting industry, just after the oil industry. The ecologically dangerous biproducts of this industry are pesticide overuse, dumping of hazardous chemicals into oceans, emissions of pollutants and widespread exploitation of industry workers.</p>
<p>Our clothing also contributes significantly to the ever-piling landfills. It is said that only 15 percent of our old clothes is recycled or donated, the rest ending up as waste at landfills. Majority of our clothes made of synthetic fibers take up to 200 years to decompose.</p>' where id=7 ;

