Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>It may seem innocent that you buy a plastic water bottle or a cup of coffee to quench your thirst. Once you drink your fill, you dispose them within an hour, never to think of them again. </p>
<p>Where do they end up and why is it a concern to the environmentalists? The sad story of plastic bottles is that 35 billion of them end up in landfills each year. The amount is staggering and so is its negative impact on the environment. Although 23 percent of these bottles are recycled, it isn’t enough to balance consumption and disposal. We are failing to find a feasible solution for these discarded single-use plastic bottles. </p>
<p>The story of single-use cups is no different. 50 billion paper cups end up in landfills. This amount is enough to create a waste mountain of coffee cups alone. To make matters worse, paper cups are not recyclable because of the plastic liner and coffee contamination.</p>' where id=10;

