Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>Nature makes sure that everything in it has a use — the rotting zucchini, as well as the lavender sprouting scented blossoms in the backyard. Food scraps and yard waste together currently make up about 30 percent of what we throw away and should be composted instead. Making compost keeps these materials out of landfills where they take up space and release methane, a potent greenhouse gas. So, how do we recycle and reuse? It’s actually just one simple process: </p>
<p>Home composting is about taking most of our leftovers, waste and unwanted extras and turn them into fertile soil. You can mix yard and kitchen waste in a pile or bin and provide the right conditions to encourage decomposition. Let bacteria go to work, recycling waste material into usable fertilizer. This can have a significant impact on the productivity of gardens and landscapes. </p>
<p>Compost also has a host of benefits. Firstly, it’s free. You get to use kitchen waste, lawn clippings, leaves – all things that you would have otherwise thrown away. Potting mixes and soils that are rich in compost produce vigorous plants regardless of whether you’re growing vegetables, growing herbs or organic rose gardening. Home composting also improves garden soil structure, texture and aeration. More importantly, it feels good. When else can you turn trash into treasure?
</p>' where id=11;

Update challenges set participation_steps ='<p>Don’t throw away organic waste. They are treasure in disguise. </p>
<ul>
<li style="padding-left:10px;">Set up your own composting pit at home. </li>
</ul>' where id=11;

Update challenges set reference ='
<p><strong>Read more: <a href="https://www.planetnatural.com/home-composting/">https://www.planetnatural.com/home-composting/</a></strong></p>' where id=11;





Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>When was last time you received or gave a gift to someone? Perhaps, not too long ago. Giving gifts to our friends and families is a very common practice. What if we said that you can use this practice to create awareness about various environmental issues in your community?  </p>
<p>Green gifting is an emerging trend that can lower the environmental impact created by gift-giving. A green gift can be any gift-worthy item as long as it is made using fewer resources and produces less waste than usual. You can choose gifts that have one or many of these qualities – non-toxic, waste reducing, sustainably-sourced, durable and minimally packaged. You could alternatively also buy something that could help somebody go green, for example – a reusable coffee mug or straw. </p>
<p>Green Gifting can be a wonderful opportunity to spread awareness, start practices like recycling and upcycling and urge your friends and family members to do the same. Even re-gifting (gifting never used or rarely used items) which is usually frowned upon - is encouraged as a viable green gifting option. The philosophy behind green gifting is to create as low an environment impact as possible. </p>' where id=12;

