Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>It is said that a glass bottle takes a million years to degrade. This means that when a glass bottle isn’t recycled, it remains like that at landfills for a really long time. Glass is primarily composed of silica—the same material as sand—and doesn’t break down even under the harshest environments. Whereas, a humble apple core takes only two months. Our waste is a far bigger problem than you can imagine. </p>
<p>You can understand this better if you visit a landfill where your neighbourhood garbage is hauled off. It will give you an idea of the humongous amount of garbage we throw out every day. Aluminum cans, discarded clothing, rubber soled shoes, plastic cups… and the list never really ends. </p>
<p>You will also be amazed at the time these things take to degenerate. </p>
<p><table>
<tr><td>Glass bottles </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> one million years</td></tr>
<tr><td>Disposable nappies </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> 450 years </td></tr>
<tr><td>Plastic bottles </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> 450 years </td></tr>
<tr><td>Plastic bags </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> 200-500 years </td></tr>
<tr><td>Aluminum cans </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> 80-200 years </td></tr>
<tr><td>Rubber-soled shoes </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> 50-80 years </td></tr>
<tr><td>Tin cans </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> 50 years </td></tr>
<tr><td>Clothing </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> Up to 40 years </td></tr>
<tr><td>Plastic film </td><td>&nbsp;-&nbsp;</td><td> 20-30 years.</td></tr>
</table></p>
<p>So, what does this tell us? That we must think of the environmental impact when we discard anything. We need to extra careful of what we throw out. The unseemly mound of discard should set us all thinking. </p>' where id=14;

