Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>Is gardening a favorite pastime of yours? If yes, do you know the composure of the fertilizers and pesticides you use? The most conveniently available and reasonable prized fertilizers and pesticides are chemical in nature. While they do increase the nutrient value of your soil and the growth of your plants, they have serious consequences when used in the long run. </p>
<p>Some of the harm chemical fertilizers may cause include waterway pollution, chemical burn to plants,
increased air pollution, groundwater contamination, acidification of the soil and mineral depletion of the soil. Used over time, they reduce the quality of your natural soil and make them extensively reliant on chemicals. Chemical pesticide exposure can have many adverse effects on us and other non-target organisms. </p>
<p>Organic alternatives to these gardening aids are the best option in terms of long term soil health and environmental impacts. As organic fertilizers and pesticides come from organic sources such animal manure and plants, they improve soil structure and increase their ability to hold water. Ultimately, they are renewable, biodegradable, sustainable, and environmentally friendly.</p>
<p>Mulching – covering soil around the plant with organic material such as grass clippings, crushed leaves, hardwood chips and pine straw – can be an adopted as an effective practice in your garden to act as natural soil conditioners. Mulching contributes to soil health, helps it retain moisture, reduces water injury and helps with weed control.
</p>' where id=15;

