Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>Have you recently visited a book shop? Stacks of books are piled up waiting for their purchaser. The books that remain on the shelves have a different story to tell. Did you know that over 1.5 million metric tons of paper is used for book publishing in the US alone? If we join the statistics of the rest of the world, this amount will staggeringly increase resulting in a worrying carbon footprint. </p>
<p>Transportation of the books from the printers to bookstores ranging across cities also add to the carbon footprint of the industry. Billions of these books published end up unpurchased. They are either sent back for pulping or end up in landfills. The sad truth is that the book industry is hurting the planet through inefficient manufacturing, distribution, and forecasting of sales.  </p>
<p>While many changes can be made in the publishing industry, as readers we can do our part in reducing the impact of environment. The most sustainable option for a print book lover is the library because books are lent out and read many times. Borrowing books satisfies your thirst of reading and at the same time saves paper, money and energy that goes into new books. </p>
<p>With the ongoing digital revolution, the popularity of e-books is on the rise. The beauty of e-books is their ready accessibility and of course their non-use of paper. They may be the easiest way to stop the destructive cycle of overprinting and pulping. </p>
<p>Donate books after reading and consider buying from used book store. They create a book cycle that do not harm the environment like printing new books do.
</p>' where id=18;

