Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>How do you dispose your waste? Do you end up throwing everything in one single bin? If yes, you might want to know that this habit is not so harmless as it might seem. </p>
<p>When you dump all kinds of waste together, you are increasing the effort taken to manually segregate waste into groups like recyclable, non-recyclable, toxic, etc. </p>
<p>Segregated waste is also often cheaper to dispose off because it does not require as much manual or mechanical sorting as mixed waste. It is also important to segregate waste in the interest of public health. In particular, hazardous wastes can cause long-term health problems, so it is very important that they are disposed off correctly and safely and not mixed in with other waste from your home or office.</p>
<p>Landfills are an increasingly pressing problem. Less and less land is available to deposit refuse, but the volume of waste is growing. As a result, segregating waste is not just of environmental importance, but also of economic concern. Effective segregation of wastes means that less waste goes to landfill which makes it cheaper and better for people and the environment. </p>
<p>The most common form of segregation is separating out recyclable waste such as paper, plastic and glass from landfill and compostable waste. The inclusion of other types of waste in recycling containers causes contamination, reducing the quality of recycled paper and plastic products. Contaminated recycled products also sell for less, a loss that gets passed on to the customer. </p>
<p>The simplest way to solve the waste problem is to solve it before it starts, by practicing proper on-site segregation of waste.
</p>' where id=23;

Update challenges set participation_steps ='
<p>Waste Segregation is the first step in a compliant waste management plan that will help the environment as well as public health. </p>
<ul>
<li style="padding-left:10px;">Segregate your waste by setting up three different bins for different kinds of waste. </li>
</ul>' where id=23;

Update challenges set reference ='
<p><strong>Here is some more information on understanding ow to segregate waste effectively: <a href="http://bengaluru.citizenmatters.in/4561-swmrt-solid-waste-management-guidelines-4561">http://bengaluru.citizenmatters.in/4561-swmrt-solid-waste-management-guidelines-4561</a></strong></p>' where id=23;



Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>Having your own kitchen garden has many benefits. Firstly, it is a great way for the whole family to be involved and engage in a relaxing and physical activity. Secondly, the fruits and vegetables grown in your own garden will be healthier because they are rich in nutrients. They also considerably reduce the money spent for transporting, water, fertilizers, etc. on the food items which you buy from supermarkets. </p>
<p>Whether you find gardening relaxing or want to adopt a healthy lifestyle by avoiding produce grown with chemicals, you can have your own kitchen garden. </p>
<p>While, traditionally, a kitchen garden is accessible directly from the kitchen, in an apartment, you can innovate to include one in any available space, whether it’s a terrace, balcony or corridor. However, ensure that the area that you choose has sufficient sunlight so that your plants can thrive</p>
<p>After considering the amount of sunlight in the area and the size of the pots, make a list of vegetables, greens and herbs that you would like to grow. Start by planting easy to grow vegetables. Usually, methi (fenugreek) and local varieties of spinach are the best options to start with. Tomato, cucumber and bitter gourd are ideal vegetables for beginner gardeners to grow. Herbs such as mint and coriander, which are used daily in Indian cooking, are also excellent choices. Once you get more confident, you can experiment with more exotic varieties such as lettuce, zucchini and coloured peppers.
</p>' where id=24;

