Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>From growing our own plants to buying from supermarkets, the human food journey has remarkably changes over centuries. Now food travels thousands of kilometers before it is served to us. Have you ever wondered who grows these plants, how they are cultivated and who benefits from them? </p>
<p>What do you know about GMOs? They are crops whose genetic makeup has been modified in laboratories using genetic engineering or transgenic technology. With modern GMOs, DNA is taken from a completely different species (like a fish or virus) and inserted into a crop (like a tomato or corn) to transfer genetic traits. </p>
<p>Today, an estimated 80% of the food on supermarket shelves contain GMOs, something not stated on ingredient labels. The long-term health effects of GMOs on both people and planet are virtually unknown. </p>
<p>At the same time, crops that are imported from long distances rarely benefit the farmer directly. Smallholder farmers produce 70% of the world’s food. Yet the global food system poses many obstacles to those who seek to earn a sustainable livelihood by farming. The products we buy today are made by many minimum-wage farmers and workers who are isolated from the huge profits made by the sales. </p>
<p>One of the way to make sure small-scale farmers get their due is to buy Fairtrade certified products. The Fairtrade mark means the product’s ingredients have been produced by small-scale farmer organizations that meet Fairtrade''s social, economic and environmental standards. At its core, Fair Trade advocates for workers like these smallholder farmers. Fair Trade supports workers’ rights, economic and community development, and environmentally friendly production methods.</p>
<p>The aim is to use trade, not aid, to help small-scale farmers; one of the most marginalized groups in the world. When, as consumers, we advocate this cause by buying Fairtrade certified products, we are helping the real producers of our food gin profits and recognition, successfully elimating middlemen monarchy.
</p>' where id=27;

Update challenges set participation_steps ='
<p>Do your share to create a global food system of fair trade and safe food. </p>
<ul>
<li style="padding-left:10px;">Identify 5 products that fall under the category of Fairtrade or non-GMO. Switch to these products. </li>
<li style="padding-left:10px;">Request your local supermarkets to carry non-GMO products. </li>
</ul>' where id=27;

Update challenges set reference ='
<p><strong>Read more about what Fair Trade and non-GMO really means: <a href="https://www.livestrong.com/slideshow/1011054-labels-organic-allnatural-nongmo-fairtrade-really-mean/?slide=1">https://www.livestrong.com/slideshow/1011054-labels-organic-allnatural-nongmo-fairtrade-really-mean/?slide=1</a></strong></p>' where id=27;



