Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>We all have our own part to play in the ecosystem. Wildlife helps in balancing the ecosystem and provides stability to different natural processes like rainfall, changing of temperature, fertility of soil etc. It is difficult to imagine our world without the millions of species of wildlife surrounding us. </p>
<p>Climate change, unregulated hunting and poaching, pollution, overexploitation and deforestation are adversely affecting wildlife, pushing increasing number of species into the endangered zone. Nurturing wildlife will positively restore balance in our local ecosystem and lend a hand to the global scene. </p>
<p>Creating a wildlife habitat in your own homes can be an excellent way of supporting local wildlife. Wildlife habitat are areas distributed horizontally and vertically across any landscape that fulfill the needs of a specific wildlife species for the basic requirements of food, water, reproduction (nesting), and protection against predators and competitors.</p>
<p>Supporting insects, birds and bees can promote pollination and increase plant life. Nurturing ground animals can increase your garden soil fertility and help them thrive as well. The benefits of such a wildlife habitat is many and is symbiotic in nature. You benefit from the very animal life you help sustain.
</p>' where id=29;

Update challenges set participation_steps ='
<p>The requirements of wildlife habitat vary according to the needs of each species. You can choose to create a species-specific wildlife habitat such as for birds, bees, insects, etc. </p>
<ul>
<li style="padding-left:10px;">Create a backyard wildlife habitat or "naturescape" in your own backyard, patio or deck by incorporating a few basic elements. </li>
<li style="padding-left:10px;">Basic elements include fresh water (i.e., a bird bath and, if in a yard, water low to the ground); plants and feeders that provide nourishment for birds, insects, etc.; and rocks, trees, bushes and/or bird houses for shelter and nesting. </li>
</ul>' where id=29;

