Update challenges set environmental_issues='
<p>Do you pack your lunch to your office? How much waste do you dispose after the meal? Paper napkins, plastic foils, plastic forks and spoons, throw-away bags, single-use cans are some of the waste generated by you during the lunch hour.</p>
<p>Inorganic waste may take hundreds of years to decompose or may not decompose at all. How much of these inorganic wastes do you contribute from your lunch box? If you discard any of the above-mentioned items during lunch, it’s time to stop now. </p>
<p>A small paper napkin may seem innocent enough. But, did you know that every ton paper needs 17 trees, 380 gallons of oil, 4,000 kilowatts of energy, 7,000 gallons of water and ultimately uses three cubic yards of space at the landfill when disposed. Using what is available to you thoughtfully and cutting back your waste generation can save these valuable resources. </p>
<p>Take a step back and consider the organic and reusable replacement to single-use materials you use. Carry a cloth towel that can be washed everyday instead of using paper napkins during lunch. Carry a thermos water bottle and say no to single-use cups and water bottles. Use cutlery from home and substitute it to plastic ones. These simple changes to your lunch box will automatically reduce your share of waste generated.
</p>' where id=30;

